WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.400
Thanks. Hi, I'm Brooke. I am a data scientist at the ACLU, and today I'm going to be talking

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:19.840
about the small role that R and data analysis played in an effort to reunify over 2,500

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:23.520
children who were separated from their families while trying to seek refuge in the United

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:27.120
States. In that context, we'll talk about how to deal

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:32.680
with extremely messy and flawed data and how to create efficient but safe ways to process

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:36.720
and analyze that data, especially when it's updated over time and especially when those

00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:42.000
updates aren't consistent or predictable. But first we have to start from the beginning

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:48.560
with the broader story of family separation. So in November of 2017, a Congolese woman

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:52.320
and her six-year-old daughter arrived at a legal port of entry in California to seek

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:59.200
asylum. They were detained together at first, but after four days in detention, ICE put

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:05.559
the child on a plane and flew her 2,000 miles away from her mother to a facility in Chicago.

00:01:05.559 --> 00:01:09.879
Before she was sent to Chicago, S, her daughter, was close enough for Ms. L to hear her screaming

00:01:09.879 --> 00:01:13.680
through the night. They only got to talk to each other around six times for the four months

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:19.160
that they were separated. In February of 2018, ACLU lawyers met with

00:01:19.160 --> 00:01:24.360
Ms. L and immediately they filed a class-action lawsuit, because already by February, it

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:32.239
was clear that this was not an isolated case. In March of 2018, Ms. L and her daughter were

00:01:32.239 --> 00:01:38.480
reunited largely in response to pressure from this litigation. But in that same month, then-DHS

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:43.760
Secretary John Kelly proposed on CNN that family separation might be a useful policy

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:52.879
to help deter immigration from Central America. In May, this policy became official and was

00:01:52.879 --> 00:01:58.519
met with immediate backlash, both from the legal community but also from activists, from

00:01:58.519 --> 00:02:03.239
regular people, from families. This was a huge story that I'm sure you saw over the

00:02:03.239 --> 00:02:08.880
summer and it really enraged everyone, as it should have.

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:14.520
In response to that, in June, on June 20th, Trump finally administered an executive order

00:02:14.520 --> 00:02:18.559
to stop the separation, but this executive order didn't have anything to do with the

00:02:18.559 --> 00:02:22.880
more than 2,000 children who were already separated. And so the judge in the Ms. L case

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:27.880
issued an injunction and ordered the government to reunite the families. And those efforts

00:02:27.880 --> 00:02:33.399
are still continuing today. Most of the families have either been reunified or their wishes

00:02:33.399 --> 00:02:38.720
have been sort of gathered and understood. But this has been a really, really long and

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:44.639
arduous process. And it's been clear the whole time that there was not a data system in place

00:02:44.639 --> 00:02:49.479
to handle the reunifications. Data started pouring in around June, which also happened

00:02:49.479 --> 00:02:54.880
to be the time that I started working at the ACLU. And so I immediately got involved with

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:59.600
the case to try to figure out how we can organize the data that was coming in.

00:02:59.639 --> 00:03:05.000
In September, the Department of Homeland Security published an internal watchdog report which

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:11.559
stated that they struggled to provide accurate, complete, and reliable data on family separations.

00:03:11.559 --> 00:03:15.759
In more day-to-day terms, what that meant was that I would get emails like this from

00:03:15.759 --> 00:03:20.960
our legal counsel with updates. Basically what would happen is every week we would get

00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:25.639
a joint status report in which the government told us the number of children that remained

00:03:25.639 --> 00:03:30.520
in various categories. And we would also get a data dump of messy Excel spreadsheets

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:37.880
that all had been artisanally handcrafted one by one. And they never seemed to add up

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:42.320
to the numbers in the joint status report. And so my role as a data scientist wasn't

00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:47.160
really to do any data science. It wasn't to make predictions or run regressions or even

00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:52.119
to calculate anything more than simple counts and averages. My role was to support the team

00:03:52.119 --> 00:03:57.679
in what they needed to find out what data was wrong, what was missing, and what families

00:03:57.679 --> 00:04:05.240
might be falling through the cracks. And that boiled down to three main actions. Organizing,

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:12.460
validating, and describing the data so that we could find people, ask new questions, and

00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:22.079
understand what was going on. Basically that means rectangulating hundreds of Excel spreadsheets,

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:27.839
finding errors and inconsistencies in those, and then calculating descriptive statistics

00:04:27.839 --> 00:04:32.920
so that we could identify individual cases that were coming to us and make sure that

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:41.440
the advocates, media, and legislators knew what was going on.

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:47.239
So for organization, here's a snapshot of the data that we've received so far. And data

00:04:47.239 --> 00:04:52.480
was still coming in as recently as December. This isn't big data by anyone's definition,

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:56.160
I don't think, but it's certainly big enough to not be able to do everything manually by

00:04:56.160 --> 00:05:03.079
just looking at one spreadsheet. And it had some quirks. For example, here are some different

00:05:03.079 --> 00:05:08.760
ways that the unique identifier, the alien number, which is kind of like a social security

00:05:08.760 --> 00:05:13.320
number for people going through this process. Here are all the different fields that we

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:21.040
could have joined on. We could call it an alien number A, or we could abbreviate child,

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:26.839
or we could call it a child or a UAC. We could call it a relative or a parent. Or we could

00:05:26.839 --> 00:05:34.559
not describe what those were, and those could vary across spreadsheets. We could just call

00:05:34.559 --> 00:05:40.679
it no. And so my immediate reaction in response to

00:05:40.679 --> 00:05:45.480
this data request was to get everything in a nice, single, tidy rectangle with all the

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:51.239
information, one row per person. But that clearly wasn't possible. One of the reasons

00:05:51.239 --> 00:05:55.399
it wasn't possible was because some of the data was simply wrong. And we couldn't just

00:05:55.399 --> 00:05:59.519
throw out the data that we knew to be bad. We had to follow up to the government to say,

00:05:59.519 --> 00:06:07.920
what is going on here? What is this error? Where is this person currently? In this case

00:06:08.399 --> 00:06:12.480
in a lot of our cases, the data source is just as important as the data itself. And

00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:15.880
I think that's a thing to keep in mind when we're doing analyses.

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:21.200
But we still like rectangles. Everybody loves rectangles. So the first step was to get everything

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:27.399
into a nice rectangle with list columns. And we did that with these packages. I really

00:06:27.399 --> 00:06:34.760
like the FS package because it includes metadata about a given file. And then we could arrange

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:41.320
those. We could sort by size or by the date that they came in. And then we could mutate

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:50.040
over various rows based on what the path string was. And we could map over all of those rows

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:54.279
and read the data in. So here's an example of what that might look

00:06:54.279 --> 00:07:04.640
like. If we read in all of the files that match this regex pattern in a given folder,

00:07:04.640 --> 00:07:11.200
we can then arrange by the time that that file was created and try to see, you know,

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:18.839
what are the updated pieces of information telling us. And once we have a handle on that,

00:07:18.839 --> 00:07:23.440
we can read all of the data in. And so we did this with a combination with a bunch of

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:30.559
tidyverse packages. Purr was really, really useful in unnesting the various sheets.

00:07:30.559 --> 00:07:36.399
So what we're doing here, just to walk through, is we're mapping over a read Excel function

00:07:36.399 --> 00:07:40.600
called Excel sheets so that we can see the names of all the different tabs. We're making

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:44.839
it so that there's one sheet per row. And then we're reading all of the data in based

00:07:44.839 --> 00:07:51.119
on those sheet names. And so once we have everything, at least in

00:07:51.119 --> 00:07:59.160
one location in R, we can start to ask questions and see if the data makes sense. And spoiler

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:07.640
alert, it often did not. Here are some examples of some errors, to put it lightly, that we

00:08:07.640 --> 00:08:13.440
found in the data. There were a lot of book-in dates that were later than people had been

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:20.279
deported or children who had been reunified before they had even been booked in. We had

00:08:20.279 --> 00:08:29.119
22 children who were reunified with themselves. And then 73 parents who had deportation dates,

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:37.679
after that essentially was not allowed anymore. And so some of these obviously are data errors,

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:44.679
but we don't know anything more about what is the location of that actual individual.

00:08:44.679 --> 00:08:49.119
And there's nothing we can do from a data perspective once we get to this point. We

00:08:49.119 --> 00:08:53.760
have to turn around and say, what is going on with these 22 rows? Because it's really

00:08:53.760 --> 00:09:00.080
important whether they were actually reunified with their parent, but the identification

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:04.080
number was entered wrong, or if they're still somewhere else. We don't know.

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:10.000
And so we did this with a series of assertions and filters to help us find errors. And so

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:18.039
we have that nice rectangle of list columns. We can unnest the data so that we have one

00:09:18.039 --> 00:09:23.320
row for every row of information. And we have tons and tons of columns because of the variable

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:29.919
name problems that you saw earlier. But this way, we can filter to which are the rows in

00:09:29.919 --> 00:09:34.320
which the child's alien number was the same as the adult's alien number. And then we can

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:39.080
look at what that path is and say, this is the Excel sheet where we have a problem. This

00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:43.640
is the source of that information, and return to that source and figure out what's going

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:49.080
on. We can also use verifications and assertions,

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:55.599
which we can put right into a tidyverse-style pipe so that we are making sure that, for

00:09:55.599 --> 00:10:00.919
example, all of the children only have one age and one gender associated with them. So

00:10:00.919 --> 00:10:07.599
if we're going to tabulate how many children under 10 are separated from their parents,

00:10:07.599 --> 00:10:13.440
we're not double counting anyone. And so once we get at least a subset of the

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:20.440
data that we feel reasonably trustworthy about, we can start to describe it. And we

00:10:22.679 --> 00:10:26.960
can start to put it in pictures. So again, if we take that pipe from before and we pipe

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:32.960
it into a ggplot, we can look just at a distribution of the ages and genders of all the children.

00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:38.799
And this patterns jump out that we might not have expected. The two big patterns in this

00:10:38.799 --> 00:10:45.799
data for me are the jump between five-year-olds and four-year-olds and the time trend of especially

00:10:47.039 --> 00:10:53.760
teen boys. So one of the sort of peculiarities of this case was that children who were zero

00:10:53.760 --> 00:11:00.760
to four were put in a special category and expedited for reunification. And so the way

00:11:01.719 --> 00:11:05.599
that was reported on, there were around 100 children who were between the ages of zero

00:11:05.599 --> 00:11:11.280
and four and around 2,500 who were older than five, which makes it seem like, okay,

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:16.039
this is bad, but maybe we're doing a better job with the youngest children. When you cut

00:11:16.039 --> 00:11:19.520
the data differently, we find out that more than 1,000 children were under the age of

00:11:19.520 --> 00:11:26.159
10 when they were separated from their families. Another important thing that we wanted to

00:11:26.159 --> 00:11:32.679
visualize, and we did this with Leaflet, is where the children were in space. So I think

00:11:32.679 --> 00:11:36.559
we think of family separation as a border problem, and it's true that most people did

00:11:36.559 --> 00:11:42.840
come in through the southern border, but that's not where they stayed. Children were sent

00:11:42.840 --> 00:11:49.840
to essentially foster care facilities all across the country. There ended up being over

00:11:49.840 --> 00:11:56.159
400 children that ended up in New York. And a common question that we would get from legislators

00:11:56.159 --> 00:12:02.119
and from state representatives were, who are the people in my state? Are there any children

00:12:02.119 --> 00:12:06.599
here? Where are they? What can I do for them? What can I do about them? Are there any parents

00:12:06.599 --> 00:12:13.200
who are here? How can, you know, how can I in Nevada or Nebraska or South Carolina, how

00:12:13.200 --> 00:12:19.719
can I be most useful? And some of those questions we weren't able to answer because the data

00:12:19.719 --> 00:12:25.400
was so poor. So one of the things that we didn't get accurate and consistent updates

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:31.440
on was reunification date. We really wanted to know how long children had been separated,

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:38.479
but we weren't able to effectively and responsibly calculate that because there was so much missingness.

00:12:38.479 --> 00:12:42.239
And there was missingness because when you don't have data about something or someone,

00:12:42.239 --> 00:12:47.919
you don't have to hold yourself accountable. And no agency was ready for this when it happened

00:12:47.919 --> 00:12:53.159
because the Office of Refugee Resettlement hadn't had to deal with the problem of reunifying

00:12:53.200 --> 00:13:00.200
children before. And this is because the data that we collect reflects what we value. And

00:13:01.679 --> 00:13:07.799
when we aren't collecting data, something or someone isn't being counted. I think this

00:13:07.799 --> 00:13:14.799
was said most succinctly and clearly by the federal judge in this case, who commented

00:13:14.799 --> 00:13:21.799
that we have methods of keeping track of the belongings and the objects of people who are

00:13:22.559 --> 00:13:28.280
coming in through this process, but we had no system in place to provide effective communication

00:13:28.280 --> 00:13:34.880
with children and to keep track of them and to eventually reunify them with their families.

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:39.719
And it became very clear that no one had really thought this out in an appropriate way before

00:13:39.719 --> 00:13:46.719
this policy was enacted. And this question of not collecting data and not counting people

00:13:47.320 --> 00:13:51.799
is really at the root of a lot of the issues that we're worried about and fighting for

00:13:51.799 --> 00:13:57.799
right now in the civil liberties space. A lot of the cases that we're fighting are really

00:13:57.799 --> 00:14:04.799
cases about who gets counted. So recently, the ACLU won a case that barred an addition

00:14:04.919 --> 00:14:11.760
of a citizenship question to the short-form census, which advocates were worried would

00:14:11.799 --> 00:14:17.559
reduce census responses in a lot of these populations that are already marginalized

00:14:17.559 --> 00:14:24.000
and already have good reason to be suspicious of government data collection. But when we

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:31.000
figure out who gets counted, we can start to make choices based on that. So another

00:14:31.039 --> 00:14:38.039
case is whether or not we record people's LGBT status in something like the census.

00:14:39.039 --> 00:14:45.359
When we don't collect that information, we don't know how we are able to make choices

00:14:45.359 --> 00:14:52.359
based on that population. And when we don't collect information and maintain a data structure

00:14:53.559 --> 00:14:57.000
for children who are separated from their families, we're making decisions about what

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:02.520
is important. Omissions in data are just as important as what we have. And that doesn't

00:15:02.520 --> 00:15:07.359
mean collect data on everything. There are a lot of reasons why a full surveillance state

00:15:07.359 --> 00:15:14.359
is inappropriate. But it's important to reflect on what we're collecting and how that reflects

00:15:16.919 --> 00:15:22.679
what we value. So I can't finish this talk without thanking

00:15:22.679 --> 00:15:29.679
all of the ACLU lawyers, all of the lawyers at other private sector firms and other nonprofits

00:15:30.559 --> 00:15:36.559
in both America, in both North America and in Central America, and all of the people

00:15:36.559 --> 00:15:41.559
who wouldn't stand for this, the people who, the literally hundreds of thousands of people

00:15:41.559 --> 00:15:46.760
who came out, who marched in the streets, who donated, who called their representatives.

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:52.760
This was a really, really motivating issue for a lot of people. And while it was devastating,

00:15:52.760 --> 00:15:59.080
there were a lot of hopeful aspects. Because even though each of these individuals in these

00:15:59.080 --> 00:16:01.919
pictures has a lot going on in their lives, they knew that this wasn't something they

00:16:01.919 --> 00:16:08.239
were going to stand for. And I imagine that group of people turned activists include a

00:16:08.239 --> 00:16:13.239
lot of people in this room. So thank you. Are there any questions?

00:16:13.239 --> 00:16:20.239
We'll have time, actually, for just one question. Is there somebody who would like to ask a

00:16:20.239 --> 00:16:27.239
question? There we go. That was awesome, first. But how easy was

00:16:39.919 --> 00:16:45.039
it to obtain data from agencies? Did you have to use, like, FOIA or some other procedure,

00:16:45.039 --> 00:16:50.200
or was it pretty much just, here you go? Yeah. The reason we got that data is because

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:56.039
we were in a case, and so we got it through discovery. And I will caveat that with the

00:16:56.039 --> 00:16:59.880
data that we got is only as good as what we got from the government. And so there are

00:16:59.880 --> 00:17:05.599
other organizations, including us, that have found other cases that weren't originally

00:17:05.599 --> 00:17:12.000
included in that class list of around 2,600 members. And so that's a really good point

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:13.719
to call out. Thank you.

